{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01AxuvGk5P9M9GruRxSezDFo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The TLS cert has SANs for `*.elasticsearch.svc` and `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, so any pod in the elasticsearch namespace should be able to use this cert. New pods named `es-data-0.es-data-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` would match `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`.\n\nNow let me proceed with the plan:\n\n1. Update existing nodes to have `node.attr.zone: primary` (update configmap, then restart pods)\n2. Create `es-data-config` ConfigMap with `node.attr.zone: secondary` and `node.roles: [data]`\n3. Create `es-data-headless` Service \n4. Create `es-data` StatefulSet with 2 replicas\n5. Create `app-data` index with routing requirement for `zone=secondary`\n\nActually, restarting the existing pods to add the zone attribute could cause downtime. Since the pods use emptyDir for data, a restart won't lose the Elasticsearch indexes themselves, but the cluster will experience disruption. Let me reconsider—I should just update the configmap with `node.attr.zone: primary` and accept the pod restarts, since the `test-index` has 1 primary and 1 replica that should handle the temporary unavailability.\n\nBut wait, I need to verify the requirement more carefully. The original nodes currently have no zone attribute, while the new nodes will have `zone=secondary`—that's technically different. However, to make the distinction explicit and verifiable, adding `zone=primary` to the original nodes would be clearer. The risk is that restarting those pods could cause issues, though the data will regenerate since it's in emptyDir.\n\nLet me simplify my approach: add `zone: primary` to the existing nodes via configmap update with rolling restarts, create new nodes with `zone: secondary`, and set up the `app-data` index to require `zone: secondary`. The rolling restarts should be safe because the test-index has replicas spread across the cluster, so there's always a copy available even if one pod goes down.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the StatefulSet uses `Parallel` pod management, which means all pods could restart simultaneously and potentially lose all data. Instead, I should avoid restarting the existing pods altogether—leave them without a zone attribute and create new nodes with `zone: secondary`, using that difference in attributes for shard allocation rather than explicit zone requirements.\n\nFor routing shards to the new nodes, I can set `index.routing.allocation.require.zone: secondary` on the `app-data` index to force all its shards onto nodes with that zone attribute. The plan is to create a separate ConfigMap, Service, and StatefulSet for the new data nodes, wait for them to join the cluster, then apply the routing policy to move the index shards over.\n\nTo make the allocation attributes clearly different, I should add `node.attr.zone: primary` to the existing nodes first by updating their ConfigMap and doing a rolling restart—I'll switch the StatefulSet to `OnDelete` update strategy so I can control the restart manually, then delete pods one at a time to avoid disruption. attributes set, the allocation filter would only match nodes with that specific attribute value. So I need to decide whether to add the zone attribute to existing nodes through a careful rolling restart, or just add it to new nodes and accept that old nodes won't have it. Since the requirement is just that new and old nodes have different attributes, option A works—new nodes get `zone=secondary` while originals have no zone attribute at all, making them clearly distinct for routing purposes.\n\nLet me plan out the full approach: I'll add `zone: primary` to the existing nodes via a rolling restart, create a new ConfigMap for the data nodes with `zone: secondary`, set up a headless service and StatefulSet for the new nodes, then configure the index routing to require the secondary